Poster

Target IP: 10.10.110.97

Scanning


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH, HTTP, and PostgreSQL.

Enumeration

Port 5432: PostgreSQL

I tried to login to this application using default credentials but I had no luck. To overcome this, I used the module scanner/postgres/postgres_login to find a working username and password.

Exploitation


I found a working credential postgres:password using the auxiliary module from above.


And now I have access to the PostgreSQL application.


I used the module multi/postgres/postgres_copy_from_program_cmd_exec to gain a foothold on the target machine. The options I set are shown in the picture above.


After running the exploit against the target machine, I now have a foothold with the session as postgres.

Privilege Escalation


The user dark has their hardcoded password of qwerty1234#!hackme saved in a file called credentials.txt in their home directory. I was able to successfully switch to this user using the new password.


Running find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null shows the user dark has access to /var/www/html/config.php. And this file contains the password p4ssw0rdS3cur3!# of the user alison.


And now I have access to the target machine as the new user alison with the new password.


And boom! The user alison can execute all commands using sudo. I now have a root shell.
